issue.title: Question: what is a suitable stress test for a vm which shared memory/stack?
issue.body:
Hi there! Sorry for bothering you. 
On https://github.com/bluealloy/revm we're working on a shared stack between contexts (along with a shared memory already implemented). While discussing (https://github.com/bluealloy/revm/pull/816#issuecomment-1768652589) we thought that maybe we can reuse some bytecode from here as a stress test. 

In particular, we're looking for a test where we go both up and down in depth; the more calls and stressful it is, the better.
Right now, I've taken a look here https://github.com/ethereum/tests/tree/develop/src/GeneralStateTestsFiller/stCallCodes but they seems to do only a few calls (granted that I could have missed the good ones here). 
I also thought that some of these could work https://github.com/ethereum/tests/tree/develop/src/GeneralStateTestsFiller/stCreate2 (e.g. `Create2OnDepth1023.json`).

In general, I'm asking if you happen to already know what tests would be good for this purpose.
Thanks a lot in advance for the help! :pray:

issue.title: precompile identification tests affected by solc optimisations
issue.body:
this tests logic is affected by solc disable optimisations
which should not happen. need to check whats going on. 
leaving it with optimisation = on for now 

```
info: (GeneralStateTests/stPreCompiledContracts/precompsEIP2929, fork: Berlin, TrInfo: d: 2, g: 0, v: 0, TrData: `:label yes :abi f(uint,uint) 0x101157 0xf..`)
info: (GeneralStateTests/stPreCompiledContracts/precompsEIP2929Cancun, fork: Cancun, TrInfo: d: 2, g: 0, v: 0, TrData: `:label yes :abi f(uint,uint) 0x101157 0xf..`)
```

comment.body:
Solved in principle. If I use `verbatim` for the call, nothing the optimizer does affects it.

It's ugly, and if I were writing the test now I'd use LLL, but using properly documented `verbatim` is easier than rewriting the whole thing.

issue.title: Invalid JSON filler files from `GeneralStateTestsFiller`
issue.body:
While parsing some of the filler files from `GeneralStateTestsFiller`, I've found some that are invalid JSON files:

* `src/GeneralStateTestsFiller/stMemoryTest/callDataCopyOffsetFiller.json` - missing comma
* `src/GeneralStateTestsFiller/stMemoryTest/calldatacopy_dejavu2Filler.json`  - missing comma

comment.body:
> that would be a weak check, since expec section validate logical part of the test
the final test post state still can have fork related changes that you might miss.

We are aware of it. Don't have a workaround for now.

> I added a fix to json parser, such invalid formats will be errored out in the future.

Thanks.

issue.title: Transcript invalid blocks in blockchain tests
issue.body:
evmone does not support rlp. Maybe some others too.

The current blockchain tests that have invalid blocks describe invalid block as rlp field only. And valid block as rlp and its json decoding into transactions, blockheader, etc.

Since long time tests now have expected exceptions, and all invalid rlp tests are moved to rlp tests.
So the invalid blocks must be valid rlps just expected to be rejected.

Proposal is to parse block from test as invalid if it has expected exception other then that invalid block will have all the same fields in tests as a valid one.

Affected: custom test runner tools
Backwards compatibility: legacy tests will break.

Question to the teams is this easy to implement in tools, is it ok? Some code might be hardcoded to expect rlp section only. 

Alternatively can have invalid blocks transcripted but in a different way than valid. Putting the json transcription into sub json section for instance.
